Electronic ammonia detection installed in pressure safety relief vent stack. Detection system activates visual alarms at the facility main control center to alert personnel of a possible ammonia leak in the chiller system.



Preventative maintenance programs are established within the maintenance department to ensure all ammonia system components are maintained in optimum operational and mechanical condition.



Continual vibration analysis of compressors and condenser fan drive shafts is provided to alert maintenance personnel of potential equipment malfunction, or failure.



Ammonia system operators receive system training from outside contractors with extensive knowledge and experience with anhydrous ammonia.



Off Site Consequence Analysis



As required by EPA RMP Submit 2004 guidelines, the worst case and alternate case release scenarios involving the accidental release of anhydrous ammonia from this facility have been calculated. The results are retained on file at the Griffith Energy facility.



Previously Griffith Energy had reported a 6/30/2013 release, however there were no on or off site impacts associated with the release.



Emergency Response



Griffith Energy's emergency plan is part of the overall facility Integrated Contingency Plan which discusses the role of employees and management in an emergency situation. 



Procedures have been developed for: 



1) Pre-emergency planning and coordination; 

2) Personnel roles and lines of authority; 

3) Training; 

4) Communication; 

5) Emergency recognition and prevention; 

6) Safe distances and places of refuge; 

7) Site security and control; 

8) Emergency alerting and response; 

9) Personal protective and emergency equipment; and 

10) Medical surveillance. 



